## introduction

<!-- visits: 5 -->

Just a fancy way of saying that the gcd is of the form $au + bv$

## intuition
Show for $m \ge n \ge 1$. $\frac{gcd(m,n)}{m}\begin{pmatrix}  m \\ n \end{pmatrix}$, e.g. $m=p$ is prime, $1\le n \le p-1$, then $p|\begin{pmatrix} p \\ n \end{pmatrix} $ (this would mean interesting things like $(a+p)^{n} \equiv a^{p}+ b^{p}$ mod p
    - By Bezouts_lemma, $\frac{gcd(m,n)}{m}\begin{pmatrix}  m \\ n \end{pmatrix} = \frac{um+vn}{m} \frac{m!}{n!(m-n)!}$
    - = $u mCn + v \frac{m-1}{(n-1)!(m-n)!}$
    - = $u mCn + v (m-1)C(n-1) \in \mathbb{Z}$

## rigour
Let $a,b$ be integers (both not zero). Then there exists integers u,v such that $gcd(a,b)=au+bv$

